'''Yasaka Shrine''' (やさかじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Gika, Minakuchi-chō, {{ill|lt=Kōka|Q847584|WD=Q847584|1=Kōka, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, Kawakare deity, ancestral deity of local development, was invited here. In {{ill|lt=794|Q30887|WD=Q30887|1=794}} (approximately {{ill|lt=Tenpyō|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} 21), when Left Minister {{ill|lt=Tachibana no Moroe|Q3135863|WD=Q3135863|1=Tachibana no Moroe}} built temple {{ill|lt=garan|Q3482038|WD=Q3482038|1=Sangharama}} at neighboring {{ill|lt=Senkō-ji (Kōka)|Q72184313|WD=Q72184313|lt=Senkō-ji|1=Senkō-ji Temple (Koka, Shiga)}}, shrine buildings were built to protect Buddhist law<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|title=Shrine introduction > Yasaka Shrine (Yasaka) ~ (Saga Ōmiya)|url=http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=556|accessdate=2019-09-30|publisher=Shiga Prefectural Shrine Association}}</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=932|Q23656|WD=Q23656|1=932}} ({{ill|lt=Jōhei (Japan)|Q1324874|WD=Q1324874|lt=Jōhei|1=Jōhei}} 2), for distribution of divine virtue, it received the title Giga Ōmiya and shrine buildings were erected at the current site<ref name=":0" />.

The honden was built in {{ill|lt=1439|Q6380|WD=Q6380|1=1439}} ({{ill|lt=Eikyō|Q1193059|WD=Q1193059|1=Eikyō}} 11)<ref name=":0" />. According to Giga Ōmiya Senkō-ji records, the honden was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1587|Q6744|WD=Q6744|1=1587}} ({{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 15), matching architectural style and methods.

After repairs in {{ill|lt=1721|Q6913|WD=Q6913|1=1721}} ({{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 6) and {{ill|lt=1866|Q7712|WD=Q7712|1=1866}} ({{ill|lt=Keiō|Q776775|WD=Q776775|1=Keiō}} 2), dismantling and restoration were performed in {{ill|lt=1959|Q5302|WD=Q5302|1=1959}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 34)<ref name=":0" />.

In the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} it was called Kawakare Shrine, later Gika Ōmiya, then Gozu Tennō Shrine, and now Yasaka Shrine<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Kōka City History Vol.8 Kōka City Encyclopedia|date=2016-12-12|year=2016|publisher=Kōka City|page=49}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
{{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Shōmu|Q349263|WD=Q349263|1=Emperor Shōmu}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Jinmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}<ref name=":0" />

=== Festivals ===

* Kawakare Festival - {{ill|lt=May 1|Q2544|WD=Q2544|1=May 1}}<ref name=":0" />
** Day before - first-age yakudoshi men carry lion head and visit all parishioner households
** Day of festival - rites in morning; from afternoon mikoshi procession (60 youths in Genroku-style costumes cross the Yasu River)
* Matoyama no Okonai - {{ill|lt=January 7|Q2228|WD=Q2228|1=January 7}}
** As a miyaza rite, prayer for health/longevity of eldest son and family prosperity, etc. Viewing not permitted.

=== Precinct shrines ===

* Tenjin Shrine
* Kumano Shrine
* Kawakare Shrine
* Hachiman Shrine
* Yasaka Shrine

=== Cultural properties ===

=== Important Cultural Property (National designation) ===

* Honden - ikken-sha nagare-zukuri, cypress-bark roof<ref name=":1" />

=== City designated cultural properties ===

* Sacred images - made in Heian period<ref name=":1" />
*Gebabashi bridge - offered by parishioners in 1699 (Genroku 12) in thanks for successful rain prayer. Elaborate arched bridge.

